<P><FONT SIZE="-1"></FONT>1. This text has LOTS of italics in it in all cantos.  James/Steve: can I leave these in knowing that
Dartmouth will be able to represent them properly?  If not, there is a HUGE amount of dog work
to be done.  I hope there is a better way.  The beginnings of most cantos seem to have a number
of boldface items as well, if not nearly so much as italic.  Same question pertains -- but these can
be fixed manually by the editors (MC and RH) with relative ease.</P>

<BR WP="BR1"><BR WP="BR2">
<P>2. Massimiliano, please note the way footnotes need to be moved, making blocks and copying
these, from the final page of each canto and embedded in text, just as here.  This takes, I find,
between 30 and 60 minutes per canto.</P>

<BR WP="BR1"><BR WP="BR2">
<P>3. James/Steve: please note that the caps. in all these citations (information between {...}) are
SMALL CAPS.  Does that make a problem for character recognition at the Dartmouth end?  If
so, can I/we do global replaces for them?  That might be tricky.</P>

<BR WP="BR1"><BR WP="BR2">
<P>4. This sign represents a superscript "o" (DDP code: +o~).  Do MC and I have to change all of
these by hand (NO, he hoped)?  I'm not sure I know how to do globals in WordPerfect that
would replace what we have with what Dartmouth might prefer (e.g., this siglum with +o~).  You
should know, perhaps, that in other files I HAVE changed the infrequent superscripts, e.g., "i" and
"m", to Dartmouth-friendly "code" (e.g., "+m~") -- but Steve will have to be sure D'mth
recognizes _this_ siglum.  To date all I know it recognizes is +o~ and +a~, and I have left all -- or
just about all -- of the superscript "a" and "o"s  that would correspond to these as they are in the
text.</P>

<BR WP="BR1"><BR WP="BR2">
<P>5. Massimiliano: please note that I have been able to break the commentaries in Inf. II into smaller
units (which we prefer for DDP), fitting them to specific lines without doing too much harm to the
flow of Pietro's argument.  In III, however, I found it just about impossible to make things smaller
than his own three divisions, and simply followed him.  This is a difficult decision that must be
made for each canto.  I am glad that you are seeing two cantos that embody different modes, and
would like to hear your opinion.</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

